        <h3 class="story-h">Building the Governance Framework — Three Pillars</h3>
        <p class="story-p">Fixing 309 issues was the immediate work. The more important question was: how do we make sure this doesn't happen again? The answer was a three-pillar governance framework — simple enough to be actually used, robust enough to catch the categories of error the audit had found.</p>
        <p class="story-p">Pillar one: a Data Dictionary defining all 74 metrics used in performance reporting, owned by the Insight & Analytics team and version-controlled. Any service area wanting a different definition had to raise it formally. No more informal variations between teams building up silently.</p>
        <p class="story-p">Pillar two: mandatory validation checkpoints — a lightweight checklist (record count reconciliation, null checks on mandatory fields, period-on-period variance flag over 5%) applied to every dataset before it entered any regulatory report. Automated in Excel where possible, manual sign-off where not.</p>
        <p class="story-p">Pillar three: an escalation protocol. Previously, an analyst who spotted an anomaly might mention it informally or not at all. The protocol made it explicit — here's the threshold for flagging, here's who to tell, here's the resolution timeline before submission. Clear accountability, at every level.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="story-visual">
        <div class="sv-label">Governance Framework — Three Pillars Implemented</div>
        <div class="pillars">
          <div class="pillar">
            <div class="pillar-icon">📖</div>
            <div class="pillar-title">Data Dictionary</div>
            <div class="pillar-desc">74 metric definitions. Single source of truth, version-controlled, reviewed quarterly. Resolved the MOSAIC/CareFirst definition conflict that had been producing inconsistent headlines for over a year.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="pillar">
            <div class="pillar-icon">🔁</div>
            <div class="pillar-title">Validation Checkpoints</div>
            <div class="pillar-desc">12-point pre-submission checklist. Record count vs. source, null checks on mandatory fields, >5% period variance triggers review. Automated in Excel; manual sign-off required before any submission leaves the team.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="pillar">
            <div class="pillar-icon">📣</div>
            <div class="pillar-title">Escalation Protocol</div>
            <div class="pillar-desc">Documented process: what triggers a flag, who it goes to, resolution timeline, and what happens if unresolved at submission. Removed the ambiguity that had previously allowed issues to be quietly buried.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="story-section">
        <h3 class="story-h">What Changed — And the Principle That Has Stayed</h3>
        <p class="story-p">Within two quarters, the validation checkpoints were catching issues that would previously have reached regulatory submissions. Not 309 of them — the culture change meant fewer were being introduced at source — but enough to confirm the system was working. The Council's data quality measurably improved, and the analytics team's relationship with the service areas shifted: from a function that processed data to one that actively protected its integrity.</p>
        <p class="story-p">The lesson that has stayed relevant across every data role since: quality is a process design problem, not an inspection problem. You cannot reliably catch errors at the end of a pipeline that doesn't have quality built in from the start. Push responsibility upstream, to the people who touch data first, where errors are cheapest to fix.</p>
      </div>

